  "why": "DRFuzz enforces naturalness through a GAN-based fidelity assurance that filters mutated inputs to resemble the natural training distribution, and it applies mutation design choices (small pixel-level edits, whole-image transforms) plus limits on mutation repetitions (max_times, seed-selection decay) to help preserve semantics. However, the paper does not enforce or measure semantic equivalence explicitly with respect to the original seed across many iterations (e.g., no explicit original-seed similarity metric or hard constraint preventing cumulative drift); controls are mostly per-step (small mutations, mutation-count limits, and discriminator thresholds derived from an initial-seed fidelity score). Therefore DRFuzz ensures semantic consistency and naturalness primarily at the successive-mutation / per-seed level rather than guaranteeing preservation relative to the original seed across iterative accumulation of changes.",
  "evidence": "Definition of regression fault (semantic assumption) — (Page 3, Section II): \"Definition 2. Regression fault. ... x is called to trigger a regression fault if x is correctly predicted by M1, yet wrongly predicted by M2, i.e., cM1[x] = y ∧ cM2[x] ≠ y.\" \n\nNaturalness enforced via GAN — (Page 4, Section III-B, GAN-based Fidelity Assurance): \"To obtain test inputs with high fidelity, DRFuzz designs a GAN-based fidelity assurance method, which first learns a discriminator via GAN to discriminate natural inputs with synthetic inputs precisely and then then utilizes it to ensure that the generated test inputs resemble natural inputs in the fuzzing process.\" \n\nHow the discriminator is used as a per-seed threshold — (Page 4, Section III-B): \"During the fuzzing process, we feed an initial seed into the Discriminator to get a fidelity score, which serves as the fidelity threshold for filtering out the low-fidelity inputs generated from this initial seed.\" \n\nMutation design to preserve semantics (per-step) — (Page 4, Section III-C, Mutation Rules): \"Pixel-Level Mutation aims to change a small set of pixels in an image... DRFuzz randomly selects a small set of pixels (i.e., 0.5% total pixels) for mutation. Image-Level Mutation aims to change the whole image... this category of mutation rules can simulate real-world scenarios more effectively when applying them to the whole image.\" \n\nControls to limit cumulative mutation (but not an explicit original-seed similarity check) — (Page 6, Section III-C2, Seed Probability Update): \"max_times is the maximum number of times a seed can be mutated, which can limit the number of similar seeds and avoid significant changes causing semantic deviations from the initial seed to some degree.\" \n\nEmpirical evidence that GAN improves fidelity (shows naturalness enforcement): (Page 9, Section IV-B2, Ablation): \"They label 86% of inputs generated by DRFuzz as high-fidelity and only 57.5% of inputs generated by DRFuzz_NG as high-fidelity. ... This indicates that the GAN-based Fidelity Assurance technique can filter out more than 20% of fault-triggering inputs with low fidelity.\""
